external_knowledge:
- High-value customers: customers with an RFM score > 50;
- Identity refers to customer_id;
- How they stack up in terms of RFM score: rfm_score;
- Best performers: ordered by rfm_score in descending order.

- Customer sentiment can be inferred from feedback ratings where a higher average rating indicates more positive sentiment; 
- The 'buzz' around a campaign can be gauged by the number of feedbacks received, with a higher count indicating more engagement or interest;
- The campaigns considered are those that were active exclusively in the month of May 2023;
- Only campaigns with at least one feedback rating are considered.

sql:
SELECT customer_name, average_order_value AS average_spending
FROM customers
ORDER BY average_order_value DESC;

external_knowledge:
- "active customers" refers to customers who made more than 5 purchases in the last 30 days; 
- "above-average feedback" indicates an average rating greater than 4;
- "highly valued" means customers with an RFM score above 50.

- RFM score typically represents a customer's value based on their purchasing behavior;
- The threshold is the benchmark set for classifying customer segments;
- 'Higher average score' refers to the group's mean RFM score being above the segment's specific threshold value.

sql:
SELECT customer_name, average_order_value
FROM customers
WHERE total_orders > (SELECT AVG(total_orders) FROM customers);

SELECT segment_name, r_rank, f_rank, m_rank
FROM rfm_scores
WHERE r_rank > 3 AND f_rank > 3 AND m_rank > 3;

SELECT rfm_score
FROM rfm_scores
ORDER BY rfm_score DESC;

SELECT segment_id, COUNT(customer_id) AS number_of_customers
FROM customer_segment_mapping
GROUP BY segment_id;
